>>114956134
file some teeth into the sides of feeler gauges and they can be used as nut slot files for the right size strings, you can also sand the edges to be rounded so they cut a round slot

for the low E&A strings you can use torch tip cleaners which are just as cheap as feeler gauges and they can do a good enough job, while also cutting a round slot (they are very slow though)

you can buy fret crowning files and dressing files for cheap on ebay and amazon, however stay away from the orange handled popsicle stick fret dressing files (they are too wide to crown properly and they are crudely made with teeth on the edges that rip your fretboard up)

>I swam competitively so this music kept me focused during the meets

>mom says no because that music is loud so it must be violent
>that Christmas they get me the Live in Texas DVD

>I say no worries, I’m just glad we appreciate the same music and that you like my favorite band
>in 2007 they come back to town

>Linkin Park sound so much better live than all of their CDs and recordings
>go to college like a week later
>hang up pic related in my dorm

I forgot to write "Minor" but you get the idea, or maybe not.
The C is the white note left of the 2 black keys.
so the C scale goes C D E F G A B C...

you can make chords out of the scale by picking 3 notes that have a note in between, so like C E G, or D F A.
Then when you look at the keyboard you can count how many notes are between those. so for C and E there are 4 "steps" you take from C to E, and 3 steps from E to G

>>114960951
There is a whole step (or 2 steps) between the I, II, and III of a major scale. e.g. C D E all have a black note in between.
II III IV would be a whole step then a half step, like D E F have a black note between D and E but not between E and F
so even though the chords are all major they would not be using the same pattern of root notes unless you are in a weird scale like whole tone or something.

I'm not an expert in what is or isn't forgotten from the 80's, but here are some songs I've picked up from /mu/ and other places that I don't really hear in other pop-culture contexts like movies or grocery store radio playlists.

>Men at Work - No Sign of Yesterday

A mournful song about technological progress and the loss of the past:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TQJ_SjMdMq4

>Scott Wilk and the Walls - Suspicion

A new wave/rock song about cheating that wasn't apparently a big hit, despite its nifty music video:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kzmO2mhxkdo

>Maanam - Night Patrol

Probably more famous in Poland/eastern Europe.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GfqXTzfewFU

>Alexander Robotnick – Ce N'est Q'un Début

Italo-disco that critics seemed to like at the time.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EDpZvuWmQZo

>Ayumi Nakamura - Friday Ballerina

Lots of 80's J-pop is popular again, but this is more of a rock-influenced J-pop song with a rougher-voiced female singer.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I3TWY_bBZO0

>Toto - Lion (Bobby Kimball demo version)

The band itself is famous, but this outtake from the Isolation sessions apparently isn't. If you can get past the horrendous production quality, it's a good vocal performance.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2oIkXfPNf3E

>Thinking Plague - Fountain of All Tears

One of the only 'rock in opposition' songs that actually sounds melodic and pretty to me.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q8YH7v-ZbT0

Get something as a reference note (keyboard, recording, whatever) and tune one string to that note, let's say the low E string. posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>no answers suggesting harmonically tuning
Bunch of amateurs I see

Play the 5th fret harmonic on the E & 7th fret harmonic on the A at the same time. Repeat for A-D & D-G. Then the 7th fret harmonic on the E and the open B. Then 7th fret harmonic on the A and open high e.

They should all hum perfectly in these pairs. This method ensures you are tuning to the open position of the strings, without bending by pressing frets. It is vital the guitar has proper intonation, which will be obvious after tuning to this method. It is also vital 1 reference string is pitch matched to the correct hertz, else the instrument will be out and the different tension will result in poor intonation even if properly intonated.

there are a few reasons. one thing is the harmonics aren't quite accurate for this purpose. another thing related to intonation, when you actually play your guitar, you press your string down, the guitar setup will be close but never quite perfect you need to account for this difference in relative pitch, so it's better to do the usual style of tuning by pressing the 5th fret of the lower string. (actually better than using a tuner).
Guitars are not really tuned the same way as other instruments due to their nature and were considered a peasant instrument for a long time. You may notice issues when/if your ear gets good and you jam with someone on a piano or someone with classical instruments like cello or flute.
There are also other odd perception related things like the most humans perceive a slightly sharp octave as sounding sweeter when played together. So watch out if you are using an octave higher for tuning.
It's easy to google for some info
https://guitargearfinder.com/faq/true-temperament-frets/#:~:text=Guitars%20are%20tuned%20to%20'equal,it%20when%20you%20play%20guitar.

posts.com:
>>114964197
>humans perceive a slightly sharp octave as sounding sweeter
That's because guitars, like pianos, have inharmonic timbres. The stiffness of the string resists bending at the bridge and the nut. The higher the harmonic, the more extreme the bending of the string, and the more the stiffness of the string resists it. This means higher harmonics effectively play on shorter strings, so they sound sharp. The effect is more noticeable with thick strings and short scale lengths. Play chords high on the neck of a bass and you'll easily hear the problem. Stretching the octaves helps the harmonics line up better and sounds more consonant. Bowed strings don't have this problem, because the slip-stick motion of the bow restarts the vibration at each cycle, so the harmonics are forced into alignment.

I was listening Scott interview and he told that with some bads who did not have tight drummer they had to use triggers for the bass drum to get it nailed with the right tempo. But as this was the age before computers and they were doing it the old school way, they had to calculate the exact amounts of hits to get it properly after the drums had been laid down.

Scott could not do it himself, so he had to resort using his buddy called "Magic Mike" and Mike would come hang out at the studio couch and calculate the exact amounts of hits with the tempo and use some math formula do they could transfer them on tape. Anyway, when the band drummer couldn't play, Scott had to resort to use services of Magic Mike.

Pretty cool story, huh? I think it was pretty comfy story

According to JYP Entertainment‘s statistics, it can cost up to a staggering ₩900 million KRW (about $786,000 USD) just to train a new K-Pop group!

These numbers are based on a hypothetical 5-member boy group. If each of the members trains for an average of 3 years, this alone would cost JYP Entertainment between ₩700 million KRW (about $611,000 USD) and ₩900 million KRW (about $786,000 USD).

A comeback for an existing group isn’t much cheaper. A mini-album with three songs costs ₩12 million krw to record and ₩15 million krw to produce. That’s a total of ₩27.0 million KRW (about $23,600 USD), just for three songs!

A single music video can cost ₩150 million KRW (about $131,000 USD). If the company were to release a music video for just half the tracks on a typical 6 track mini-album, it would cost them ₩450 million KRW (about $393,000 USD), plus the album’s jacket shooting cost of ₩20.0 million KRW (about $17,500 USD) !

And the price of a mini-album is nothing compared to the marketing costs. Promoting an existing group’s comeback through music broadcasts costs ₩500 million KRW (about $437,000 USD)!

That ₩500 million includes: ₩50.0 million KRW (about $43,700 USD) for choreography,₩100 million KRW (about $87,300 USD) for backup dancers, ₩170 million KRW (about $148,000 USD) for stage outfits (worn for 6 weeks of promotions, to 4 music shows a week), and ₩10.0 million KRW (about $8,730 USD) just for stage makeup! Viral marketing costs another ₩150 million KRW (about $131,000 USD), while processing and other miscellaneous costs run up to ₩2.00 million KRW (about $1,750 USD).

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114964976
Try writing for parts/voices instead of chords. Write a melody, then write another melody that you can play at the same time under or with the main melody that supports or counters it, then write another melody that serves as a bass line, etc. They can be very distinct parts or closely follow each other much more like the notes in normal chord playing would. You can of course add more voices/parts or just have two, four is common. This can be a lot harder to do well than it sounds in theory but it's fun to play around with.

posts.com: Break up / mute your chords in rhythmically interesting ways. Rhythm guitar doesn't have to be an uninterrupted bed. Leave larger and larger spaces between chords. Play licks between them.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114964976
Add chromatic passing notes. Or emphasize the chromatic notes if you want to be edgy. Look at modes for ways of doing this. Or use a different rhythm with different types of muting patterns etc.

>>114964976
I just pull up sheet music for piano covers and do whatever’s possible and practical. I usually include the vocal part and try to make it an accurate cover though. If you’re just playing rhythm then arpeggiate, play the notes in different patterns. Strum and then pick an individual note, mute, add passing tones that aren’t in the chord or suspensions, as other anons said. I like the pick the bass notes so you have a cool bassline that adds interest
